#DESCRIPTION
#Sequences. Find the limit.
#ENDDESCRIPTION

#KEYWORDS('Sequences', 'convergence')

DOCUMENT();        # This should be the first executable line in the problem.

loadMacros(
"PG.pl",
"PGbasicmacros.pl",
"PGchoicemacros.pl",
"PGanswermacros.pl",
"PGauxiliaryFunctions.pl"
);

TEXT(&beginproblem);
$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;

$a = random(2,9,1);
$b = random(2,7,1);
$ans1 = "($b/(t- $a)-$b/(x- $a))/(t-x)";
$num = "$b*(x-t)";
$denom = "(t- $a)*(x- $a)*(t- x)";
$cancel = "t-x";
$num2 = "- $b";
$denom2 = "(t- $a)*(x- $a)";
$ans2 = "- $b/(x- $a)**2";

BEGIN_TEXT
Let \(f(x)=\frac{$b}{x- $a}\). Then according to the definition of derivative
$BR
\(f'(x) = \lim_{t\to x}\)\{ans_rule(30)\}$BR
(Your answer above and the next few answers below will involve the variables
\(t\) and \(x\).)$BR
The expression inside the limit simplifies to a simple fraction with $BR
numerator \(=\) \{ans_rule(30)\} $BR
and denominator \(=\) \{ans_rule(40)\} $BR
We can cancel the common factor \{ans_rule(25)\} from the numerator and
denominator leaving a simpler fraction with $BR
numerator \(=\) \{ans_rule(30)\} $BR
and denominator \(=\) \{ans_rule(40)\} $BR
Taking the limit of this fractional expression gives us $BR
\(f'(x) = \) \{ans_rule(30)\}

END_TEXT

&ANS(multivar_function_cmp($ans1,["x","t"]));
&ANS(multivar_function_cmp($num,["x","t"]));
&ANS(multivar_function_cmp($denom,["x","t"]));
&ANS(multivar_function_cmp($cancel,["x","t"]));
&ANS(multivar_function_cmp($num2,["x","t"]));
&ANS(multivar_function_cmp($denom2,["x","t"]));
&ANS(function_cmp($ans2));


ENDDOCUMENT();        # This should be the last executable line in the problem.

